{"title_page": "La Foa", "text_new": "{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = La Foa\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|province               = [[South Province, New Caledonia|South Province]]\n|map size               = 270px\n|adjustable map         = la-foa.PNG\n|map caption            = Location of the commune (in red) within New Caledonia\n|INSEE                  = 98813\n|postal code            = 98880\n|mayor                  = [[Corinne Voisin]]\n|term                   =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|-21.7115|165.8182|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 20\n|elevation min m        = 0\n|elevation max m        = 1058\n|area km2               = 464.0\n|population             = 3552\n|population date        = 2019 census\n|ethnic                 = [[Kanak people|Kanak]]s 28.06%<br>[[European ethnic groups|European]]s 24.93%<br>Wallisians and Futunans 22.76%<br>[[Multiracial|Mixed]] 12.51%<br>Other 3.9%\n|ethnic date            = 2014 census\n}}\n[[File:O'kono hache c\u00e9r\u00e9monielle Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie MHNT.jpg|thumb|''O'kono'' ceremonial ax - La Foa [[MHNT]]]]\n'''La Foa'''  is a [[commune in France|commune]] in the [[South Province, New Caledonia|South Province]] of [[New Caledonia]], an overseas territory of [[France]] in the [[Pacific Ocean]].\n\nAlthough the provincial seat of the South Province is in [[Noum\u00e9a]], La Foa was made the chief town of the administrative subdivision of the South in order to counterbalance the overwhelming weight of Noum\u00e9a in New Caledonia. Both entities share an almost identical territory, but their status and role is quite different: the South Province, with its provincial assembly in Noum\u00e9a, is a full political division, whereas the administrative subdivision of the South is only an administrative division of the French central state, akin to an ''[[arrondissement in France|arrondissement]]'' of [[Metropolitan France]], with a Deputy Commissioner of the Republic (''commissaire d\u00e9l\u00e9gu\u00e9 de la R\u00e9publique''), akin to a [[subprefecture|subprefect]] of metropolitan France, in residence in La Foa.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lafoa.nc/ Commune de La Foa - Official site]\n{{wikivoyage-inline}}\n\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage}}\n\n{{Administrative divisions of New Caledonia}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes of New Caledonia]]\n\n\n{{NewCaledonia-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = La Foa\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|province               = [[South Province, New Caledonia|South Province]]\n|map size               = 300px\n|adjustable map         = la-foa.PNG\n|map caption            = Location of the commune (in red) within New Caledonia\n|INSEE                  = 98813\n|postal code            = 98880\n|mayor                  = [[Corinne Voisin]]\n|term                   =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|-21.7115|165.8182|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 20\n|elevation min m        = 0\n|elevation max m        = 1058\n|area km2               = 464.0\n|population             = 3552\n|population date        = 2019 census\n|ethnic                 = [[Kanak people|Kanak]]s 28.06%<br>[[European ethnic groups|European]]s 24.93%<br>Wallisians and Futunans 22.76%<br>[[Multiracial|Mixed]] 12.51%<br>Other 3.9%\n|ethnic date            = 2014 census\n}}\n[[File:O'kono hache c\u00e9r\u00e9monielle Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie MHNT.jpg|thumb|''O'kono'' ceremonial ax - La Foa [[MHNT]]]]\n'''La Foa'''  is a [[commune in France|commune]] in the [[South Province, New Caledonia|South Province]] of [[New Caledonia]], an overseas territory of [[France]] in the [[Pacific Ocean]].\n\nAlthough the provincial seat of the South Province is in [[Noum\u00e9a]], La Foa was made the chief town of the administrative subdivision of the South in order to counterbalance the overwhelming weight of Noum\u00e9a in New Caledonia. Both entities share an almost identical territory, but their status and role is quite different: the South Province, with its provincial assembly in Noum\u00e9a, is a full political division, whereas the administrative subdivision of the South is only an administrative division of the French central state, akin to an ''[[arrondissement in France|arrondissement]]'' of [[Metropolitan France]], with a Deputy Commissioner of the Republic (''commissaire d\u00e9l\u00e9gu\u00e9 de la R\u00e9publique''), akin to a [[subprefecture|subprefect]] of metropolitan France, in residence in La Foa.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lafoa.nc/ Commune de La Foa - Official site]\n{{wikivoyage-inline}}\n\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage}}\n\n{{Administrative divisions of New Caledonia}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes of New Caledonia]]\n\n\n{{NewCaledonia-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Foa"}
{"title_page": "Abel Davies", "text_new": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n|                   name = Abel Davies\n|                  image = Abel Christmas Davies.jpg\n|                caption = \n|              birth_name = Abel Christmas Davies\n|               nickname = \n|           birth_place = [[Narberth, Pembrokeshire|Narberth]], [[Wales]]\n|           death_place =\n|                 height = \n|                 weight = \n|            ru_position = [[Wing (rugby union)|Wing]]\n|        ru_amateuryears = \n|        ru_amateurclubs = [[London Welsh RFC]]<br/>[[United Hospitals RFC]]<br/>[[Llanelli RFC]]\n|          ru_amclubcaps =\n|        ru_amclubpoints =\n|            ru_amupdate = \n|        ru_nationalteam = [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]]<ref>[http://www.wru.co.uk/12750_14256.php?player=25873&includeref=dynamic Rugby Union player profiles]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|       ru_nationalyears = 1889\n|        ru_nationalcaps = 1\n|      ru_nationalpoints = (0)\n|            ru_ntupdate = \n|          ru_coachclubs = \n|          ru_coachyears = \n|         ru_coachupdate = \n|                  other = \n|             occupation = doctor\n|                 spouse = \n|               children = \n|              relatives = \n|                 school = \n|             university = [[University College London]]\n|                    website =\n}}\n\n'''Abel Christmas Davies''' (1861 &ndash; 18 June 1914) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] international [[rugby union]] wing who played club rugby for [[London Welsh RFC|London Welsh]] and international rugby for [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]]. Davies was a tall but powerful wing, and was noted as being able to sprint the 100 yards in exactly ten seconds.<ref name=\"Jones14\">Jones (1985), pg 14.</ref>\n\n==Rugby career==\nDavies came to note as a rugby player when representing London Welsh, while studying medicine in London. He was part of the London Welsh team which face the touring [[1888-1889 New Zealand Native football team|New Zealand Natives]] in February 1889. Although London Welsh lost 2-1, Davies scored the try against the Maoris.\n\nIt was while playing for London Welsh that Davies was selected to represent Wales as part of the [[1889 Home Nations Championship]]; becoming the third player from the club to be chosen for their country that season. The other representatives being [[Rowley Thomas]] and [[Martyn Jordan]]. Davies made his Wales debut on 2 March, at [[St. Helen's Rugby and Cricket Ground|St Helen's]] in a game against Ireland. Captained by Wales legendary player [[Arthur Gould (rugby player)|Arthur 'Monkey' Gould]], Davies was one of three players to make just a single-cap appearance during the game, along with [[Llanelli RFC|Llanelli's]] [[Giotto Griffiths]] and [[Tom Morgan (rugby player)|Thomas Morgan]]. The Irish won the game by two [[Try (rugby)|ties]] to nil and was the first Irish win in Wales. Davies lost his position in the next season to [[Percy Lloyd]] and was never selected for Wales again.\n\n===International matches played===\n'''Wales'''<ref name=\"Smith464\">Smith (1980), pg 464.</ref>\n* {{ru|IRE}} 1889\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |last=Godwin |first=Terry |title=The International Rugby Championship 1883-1983 |year=1984 |publisher=Willow Books |location=Grafton Street, London |isbn=0-00-218060-X}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jones |first=Stephen |author2=Paul Beken |title=Dragon in Exile, The Centenary History of London Welsh R.F.C. |year=1985 |publisher=Springwood Books |location=London |isbn=0-86254-125-5}}\n* {{cite book |last=Smith |first=David |author2=Williams, Gareth |title=Fields of Praise: The Official History of The Welsh Rugby Union |year=1980 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff |isbn=0-7083-0766-3}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Abel}}\n[[Category:Welsh rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Wales international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union wings]]\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1914 deaths]]\n[[Category:London Welsh RFC players]]\n[[Category:Llanelli RFC players]]\n[[Category:19th-century Welsh medical doctors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh medical doctors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n|                   name = Abel Davies\n|                  image = \n|                caption = \n|              birth_name = Abel Christmas Davies\n|               nickname = \n|           birth_place = [[Narberth, Pembrokeshire|Narberth]], [[Wales]]\n|           death_place =\n|                 height = \n|                 weight = \n|            ru_position = [[Wing (rugby union)|Wing]]\n|        ru_amateuryears = \n|        ru_amateurclubs = [[London Welsh RFC]]<br/>[[United Hospitals RFC]]<br/>[[Llanelli RFC]]\n|          ru_amclubcaps =\n|        ru_amclubpoints =\n|            ru_amupdate = \n|        ru_nationalteam = [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]]<ref>[http://www.wru.co.uk/12750_14256.php?player=25873&includeref=dynamic Rugby Union player profiles]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|       ru_nationalyears = 1889\n|        ru_nationalcaps = 1\n|      ru_nationalpoints = (0)\n|            ru_ntupdate = \n|          ru_coachclubs = \n|          ru_coachyears = \n|         ru_coachupdate = \n|                  other = \n|             occupation = doctor\n|                 spouse = \n|               children = \n|              relatives = \n|                 school = \n|             university = [[University College London]]\n|                    website =\n}}\n\n'''Abel Christmas Davies''' (1861 &ndash; 18 June 1914) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] international [[rugby union]] wing who played club rugby for [[London Welsh RFC|London Welsh]] and international rugby for [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]]. Davies was a tall but powerful wing, and was noted as being able to sprint the 100 yards in exactly ten seconds.<ref name=\"Jones14\">Jones (1985), pg 14.</ref>\n\n==Rugby career==\nDavies came to note as a rugby player when representing London Welsh, while studying medicine in London. He was part of the London Welsh team which face the touring [[1888-1889 New Zealand Native football team|New Zealand Natives]] in February 1889. Although London Welsh lost 2-1, Davies scored the try against the Maoris.\n\nIt was while playing for London Welsh that Davies was selected to represent Wales as part of the [[1889 Home Nations Championship]]; becoming the third player from the club to be chosen for their country that season. The other representatives being [[Rowley Thomas]] and [[Martyn Jordan]]. Davies made his Wales debut on 2 March, at [[St. Helen's Rugby and Cricket Ground|St Helen's]] in a game against Ireland. Captained by Wales legendary player [[Arthur Gould (rugby player)|Arthur 'Monkey' Gould]], Davies was one of three players to make just a single-cap appearance during the game, along with [[Llanelli RFC|Llanelli's]] [[Giotto Griffiths]] and [[Tom Morgan (rugby player)|Thomas Morgan]]. The Irish won the game by two [[Try (rugby)|ties]] to nil and was the first Irish win in Wales. Davies lost his position in the next season to [[Percy Lloyd]] and was never selected for Wales again.\n\n===International matches played===\n'''Wales'''<ref name=\"Smith464\">Smith (1980), pg 464.</ref>\n* {{ru|IRE}} 1889\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |last=Godwin |first=Terry |title=The International Rugby Championship 1883-1983 |year=1984 |publisher=Willow Books |location=Grafton Street, London |isbn=0-00-218060-X}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jones |first=Stephen |author2=Paul Beken |title=Dragon in Exile, The Centenary History of London Welsh R.F.C. |year=1985 |publisher=Springwood Books |location=London |isbn=0-86254-125-5}}\n* {{cite book |last=Smith |first=David |author2=Williams, Gareth |title=Fields of Praise: The Official History of The Welsh Rugby Union |year=1980 |publ