{"title_page": "Michael Eisen", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Michael Eisen\n| birth_name = Michael Bruce Eisen\n|image             = Plos eisen.jpg \n|caption           = Michael Eisen\n| birth_date  ={{Birth date and age|1967|04|13}}\n|birth_place       = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]\n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = American\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Biology]] \n* [[Genetics]] \n* [[Genomics]] \n* [[Evolution]] \n* [[Developmental biology|Development]]<ref name=\"googlescholar\">{{GoogleScholar|z2foFg4AAAAJ}}</ref>}}\n|work_institutions = [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n|alma_mater        = [[Harvard College]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Don Craig Wiley]]{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n| thesis_title = Structural Studies of Influenza A Virus Proteins\n| thesis_url = https://books.google.com/books?id=e2wAHwAACAAJ\n| thesis_year = 1996\n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = [[PLOS|Public Library of Science (PLOS)]]\n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = [[Benjamin Franklin Award (Bioinformatics)]] (2002)\n|religion          = \n|footnotes         = \n|signature         =\n| website = {{Plainlist|\n* {{URL|eisenlab.org}}\n* {{URL|michaeleisen.org}}\n*{{URL|https://twitter.com/SenatorPhD}}}}\n\n}}'''Michael Bruce Eisen''' (born April 13, 1967) is an American computational biologist and the editor-in-chief of the journal [[eLife]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elifesciences.org/inside-elife/7eb55710/elife-welcomes-michael-eisen-as-editor-in-chief|title=eLife welcomes Michael Eisen as Editor-in-Chief|date=2019-03-05|website=eLife|language=en|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>. He is a professor of [[genetics]], [[genomics]] and [[Developmental biology|development]] at [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael B. Eisen, PhD|url=http://www.hhmi.org/scientists/michael-b-eisen|work=Howard Hughes Medical Institute|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"scopus\">{{Scopus|id=7004331829}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 10963602\n| year = 2000\n| last1 = Perou\n| first1 = C. M.\n| title = Molecular portraits of human breast tumours\n| journal = Nature\n| volume = 406\n| issue = 6797\n| pages = 747\u201352\n| last2 = S\u00f8rlie\n| first2 = T\n| last3 = Eisen\n| first3 = M. B.\n| last4 = Van De Rijn\n| first4 = M\n| last5 = Jeffrey\n| first5 = S. S.\n| last6 = Rees\n| first6 = C. A.\n| last7 = Pollack\n| first7 = J. R.\n| last8 = Ross\n| first8 = D. T.\n| last9 = Johnsen\n| first9 = H\n| last10 = Akslen\n| first10 = L. A.\n| last11 = Fluge\n| first11 = O\n| last12 = Pergamenschikov\n| first12 = A\n| last13 = Williams\n| first13 = C\n| last14 = Zhu\n| first14 = S. X.\n| last15 = L\u00f8nning\n| first15 = P. E.\n| last16 = B\u00f8rresen-Dale\n| first16 = A. L.\n| last17 = Brown\n| first17 = P. O.\n| last18 = Botstein\n| first18 = D\n| doi = 10.1038/35021093\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.283.5398.83| title = The Transcriptional Program in the Response of Human Fibroblasts to Serum| journal = Science| volume = 283| issue = 5398| pages = 83\u20137| year = 1999| last1 = Iyer | first1 = V. R. | pmid=9872747}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 10700174\n| year = 2000\n| last1 = Ross\n| first1 = D. T.\n| title = Systematic variation in gene expression patterns in human cancer cell lines\n| journal = Nature Genetics\n| volume = 24\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 227\u201335\n| last2 = Scherf\n| first2 = U\n| last3 = Eisen\n| first3 = M. B.\n| last4 = Perou\n| first4 = C. M.\n| last5 = Rees\n| first5 = C\n| last6 = Spellman\n| first6 = P\n| last7 = Iyer\n| first7 = V\n| last8 = Jeffrey\n| first8 = S. S.\n| last9 = Van De Rijn\n| first9 = M\n| last10 = Waltham\n| first10 = M\n| last11 = Pergamenschikov\n| first11 = A\n| last12 = Lee\n| first12 = J. C.\n| last13 = Lashkari\n| first13 = D\n| last14 = Shalon\n| first14 = D\n| last15 = Myers\n| first15 = T. G.\n| last16 = Weinstein\n| first16 = J. N.\n| last17 = Botstein\n| first17 = D\n| last18 = Brown\n| first18 = P. O.\n| doi = 10.1038/73432\n| url = https://cdr.lib.unc.edu/concern/articles/9p290c45r\n}}</ref> He is a leading advocate of [[Open access (publishing)|open access scientific publishing]] and is co-founder of [[PLOS|Public Library of Science (PLOS)]]. In 2018, Eisen announced his candidacy [[United States Senate election in California, 2018|U.S. Senate from California]] as an [[Independent politician|Independent]], though he failed to qualify for the ballot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/01/qa-michael-eisen-bids-be-first-fly-biologist-us-senate|title=Q&A: Michael Eisen bids to be first fly biologist in the U.S. Senate|last=CohenJan. 27|first=Jon|last2=2017|date=2017-01-27|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13|last3=Pm|first3=3:30}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in Boston, Eisen and his brother [[Jonathan Eisen|Jonathan]] were raised in a family of scientists. Their grandfather was an [[X-ray crystallography|x-ray crystallographer]], their father, Howard Eisen a physician, and mother, Laura<ref name=\"Laura Eisen Washington Post\">{{cite web|last1=Okie|first1=Susan|title=NIH SCIENTIST A SUICIDE AMID PROBE OF PAPER|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1987/02/14/nih-scientist-a-suicide-amid-probe-of-paper/e0cd2abe-4763-40f4-b839-8e86df4b2cbd/|work=Washington Post|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref> a biochemist. They moved to [[Bethesda, Maryland]] when Eisen was four or five years old. The brothers spent summers in Long Island with their grandparents. Eisen states that he loved frogs and salamanders '\"Even more than I have a frog fetish, I have a swamp fetish. I really like being in swamps.\"'  He was also very interested in math and was captain of the high school math team. Eisen graduated from [[Walt Whitman High School (Bethesda, Maryland)|Walt Whitman High School]] in 1985. Intending to major in mathematics at Harvard University, he realized that there [he may encounter] other more brilliant math students, it was a ''[[Good Will Hunting]]'' moment and he decided that he did not want to major in mathematics, '\"You don't want to be Salieri to Mozart.\"' During his years at Harvard, Eisen worked on \"unlocking the three-dimensional structures of proteins.\" He was shown a [[DNA microarray]] which taught him a '\"new way of doing biology\"'.<ref name=\"Mechanic Mother Jones\">{{cite web|last1=Mechanic|first1=Michael|title=Steal This Research Paper! (You Already Paid for It.)|url=https://www.motherjones.com/media/2013/09/michael-eisen-plos-open-access-aaron-swartz|publisher=Mother Jones|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nEisen completed his PhD at [[Harvard University]] in biophysics and a B.S. (also from Harvard) in Math.<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\"/>  He was under the supervision of [[Don Craig Wiley]]<ref name=\"India Bio Science\"/> while studying [[Influenza A virus]] Proteins.<ref name=\"eisenphd\">{{cite thesis|degree=PhD|first=Michael Bruce |last=Eisen|title=Structural Studies of Influenza A Virus Proteins|publisher=Harvard University |date=1996|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e2wAHwAACAAJ| authorlink=Michael Eisen|oclc=48938206}}</ref>\n\n{{Cquote|There are things that are really really difficult, those are the kinds of problems you do want to work on. It's not that easy to tell the difference between impossible problems and a problem that is really really difficult. But learning to do so is critically important. - Things I learned from working with Pat Brown - 2015 <ref name=\"India Bio Science\"/>}}\n\nAfter earning his doctorate, Eisen was a Postdoctoral Fellow at [[Stanford University]] in the lab of [[David Botstein]], where he most notably developed a method for interpreting gene expression data from microarrays. The seminal research publication that Eisen authored about this project has been cited over 16,000 times.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Eisen|first1=MB|last2=Spellman|first2=PT|last3=Brown|first3=PO|last4=Botstein|first4=D|title=Cluster analysis and display of genome-wide expression patterns|journal=Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A|date=8 December 1998|volume=95|issue=25|pages=14863\u20138|pmid=9843981|doi=10.1073/pnas.95.25.14863|pmc=24541}}</ref>\n\n=== Baseball and biology ===\n\nWhen Eisen lived in Tennessee he worked as a [[Sports commentator|play-by-play announcer]] for a minor league baseball team,<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\"/> the [[Columbia Mules]]. He is <!-- 8===8 --> a self-proclaimed [[Red Sox]] fanatic.<ref name=\"Mechanic Mother Jones\"/> He and computational biologist, James Fraser recorded a video for iBiology about the role baseball statistics influenced their research. Their argument is that sequencing DNA is similar to scoring a baseball game, and that many computational biologists learned to think about science computations from an obsessive interest in baseball stats. The exercise of comparing a specific player's stats to a database of other similar players allows a baseball fan to predict future performance. This same system works with proteins and predicting functions. As tools are developed that break down and track all stats concerning baseball players, so will technology improve with genetics. With both baseball and genetics, tools are being developed that refine the models.<ref name=\"Fraser Eisen Baseball\">{{cite web|title=James Fraser & Michael Eisen: Baseball Meets Biology|url=https://www.ibiology.org/ibiomagazine/issue-6/james-fraser-michael-eisen-baseball-meets-biology.html|website=Education|publisher=iBiology|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>  In a lecture in 2015, Eisen stated that he received a computer from his grandfather for his twelfth birthday and spent the next five years teaching himself how to program so that he could keep track of baseball stats.<ref name=\"India Bio Science\">{{cite web|title=Michael Eisen: Baseball, mathematics and biology|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BACy6Lsi6-U|publisher=India Bio Science|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nHis academic research focuses on the [[evolution]] of [[gene regulation]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Eisen | first1 = M. \n| authorlink1 = Michael Eisen\n| last2 = Spellman | first2 = P. \n| last3 = Brown | first3 = P. \n| authorlink3 = Patrick O. Brown\n| last4 = Botstein | first4 = D. \n| authorlink4 = David Botstein\n| title = Cluster analysis and display of genome-wide expression patterns \n| journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America \n| volume = 95 \n| issue = 25 \n| pages = 14863\u201314868 \n| year = 1998 \n| pmid = 9843981 \n| pmc = 24541 | doi=10.1073/pnas.95.25.14863\n}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Alizadeh | first1 = A. A. | last2 = Eisen | first2 = M. B. | authorlink2 = Michael Eisen | last3 = Davis | first3 = R. E. | last4 = Ma | first4 = C. | last5 = Lossos | first5 = I. S. | last6 = Rosenwald | first6 = A. | last7 = Boldrick | first7 = J. C. | last8 = Sabet | first8 = H. | last9 = Tran | first9 = T. | last10 = Yu | first10 = X. | last11 = Powell | first11 = J. I. | last12 = Yang | first12 = L. | last13 = Marti | first13 = G. E. | last14 = Moore | first14 = T. | last15 = Hudson Jr | first15 = J. | last16 = Lu | first16 = L. | last17 = Lewis | first17 = D. B. | last18 = Tibshirani | first18 = R. | last19 = Sherlock | first19 = G. | last20 = Chan | first20 = W. C. | last21 = Greiner | first21 = T. C. | last22 = Weisenburger | first22 = D. D. | last23 = Armitage | first23 = J. O. | last24 = Warnke | first24 = R. | last25 = Levy | first25 = R. | last26 = Wilson | first26 = W. | last27 = Grever | first27 = M. R. | last28 = Byrd | first28 = J. C. | last29 = Botstein | first29 = D. | last30 = Brown | first30 = P. O. | title = Distinct types of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma identified by gene expression profiling | journal = Nature | volume = 403 | issue = 6769 | pages = 503\u2013511 | year = 2000 | pmid = 10676951 | doi = 10.1038/35000501}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 17994087\n| year = 2007\n| last1 = Drosophila 12 Genomes\n| first1 = Consortium\n| title = Evolution of genes and genomes on the Drosophila phylogeny\n| journal = Nature\n| volume = 450\n| issue = 7167\n| pages = 203\u201318\n| last2 = Clark\n| first2 = A. G.\n| last3 = Eisen\n| first3 = M. B.\n| authorlink3 = Michael Eisen\n| last4 = Smith\n| first4 = D. R.\n| last5 = Bergman\n| first5 = C. M.\n| last6 = Oliver\n| first6 = B\n| last7 = Markow\n| first7 = T. A.\n| last8 = Kaufman\n| first8 = T. C.\n| last9 = Kellis\n| first9 = M\n| last10 = Gelbart\n| first10 = W\n| last11 = Iyer\n| first11 = V. N.\n| last12 = Pollard\n| first12 = D. A.\n| last13 = Sackton\n| first13 = T. B.\n| last14 = Larracuente\n| first14 = A. M.\n| last15 = Singh\n| first15 = N. D.\n| last16 = Abad\n| first16 = J. P.\n| last17 = Abt\n| first17 = D. N.\n| last18 = Adryan\n| first18 = B\n| last19 = Aguade\n| first19 = M\n| last20 = Akashi\n| first20 = H\n| last21 = Anderson\n| first21 = W. W.\n| last22 = Aquadro\n| first22 = C. F.\n| last23 = Ardell\n| first23 = D. H.\n| last24 = Arguello\n| first24 = R\n| last25 = Artieri\n| first25 = C. G.\n| last26 = Barbash\n| first26 = D. A.\n| last27 = Barker\n| first27 = D\n| last28 = Barsanti\n| first28 = P\n| last29 = Batterham\n| first29 = P\n| last30 = Batzoglou\n| first30 = S\n| display-authors = 29\n| doi = 10.1038/nature06341\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1091/mbc.9.12.3273| title = Comprehensive Identification of Cell Cycle-regulated Genes of the Yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae by Microarray Hybridization| journal = Molecular Biology of the Cell| volume = 9| issue = 12| pages = 3273\u201397| year = 1998| last1 = Spellman | first1 = P. T.| last2 = Sherlock | first2 = G.| last3 = Zhang | first3 = M. Q.| last4 = Iyer | first4 = V. R.| last5 = Anders | first5 = K.| last6 = Eisen | first6 = M. B.| last7 = Brown | first7 = P. O.| last8 = Botstein | first8 = D.| last9 = Futcher | first9 = B. | pmid=9843569 | pmc=25624}}</ref> Despite this focus, Eisen\u2019s work has historically spanned very diverse disciplines. For example, his 5 most cited papers  cover a broad range of topics including methods for [[hierarchical clustering]]<ref name=\":1\" />, applications to human [[Breast cancer|breast cancers]] (with [[David Botstein]] and Charles Perou)<ref name=\":0\" />, and discovery of tumor subtypes in [[Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma|diffuse large B cell lymphoma]] (with [[Ash Alizadeh]] and [[Louis Staudt]])<ref name=\":2\" />. His more research work has been on [[Drosophilidae|fruit flies]] and [[Drosophila]]<ref name=\"HarmonNYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/06/science/donald-trump-scientists-politics.html?smprod=nytcore-ipad&smid=nytcore-ipad-share&_r=1|title=In Age of Trump, Scientists Show Signs of a Political Pulse|last1=Harmon|first1=Amy|author2=Henry Fountain|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=NYT|accessdate=7 February 2017|date=2017-02-06}}</ref> and how they \"develop from a tiny single-celled egg to a mature adult. He says they hold insights into what goes wrong in people as they age.\"<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\"/> He receives funding from the [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]] for his research.<ref name=\"HarmonNYT\"/>\n\n==2018 U.S. Senate race==\nEisen announced through Twitter on January 25 his intent to run for [[2018 United States Senate election in California|U.S. Senate from California in 2018]] for Democratic Senator [[Dianne Feinstein]]'s seat, registering the Twitter handle ''SenatorPhD''.<ref name=\"Reardon Nature\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/news/geneticist-launches-bid-for-us-senate-1.21381|title=Geneticist launches bid for US Senate|last1=Reardon|first1=Sara|journal=Nature|accessdate=7 February 2017|doi=10.1038/nature.2017.21381|year=2017}}</ref> His campaign slogan was \"Liberty, Equality, Reality\". Eisen's reasons for running for Congress included his belief that the [[Donald Trump|Trump administration]] is unresponsive to [[climate change]] and other science-related issues. Another reason Eisen decided to run was his experience watching Cabinet appointees being interviewed by the Senate about climate change. He thought '\u201cIt would be really nice to have scientists ask the questions of the Cabinet appointees, because the senators don\u2019t seem to understand the issue and aren\u2019t asking the right questions.\u201d'<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\" /> He feels that if science is to be on the forefront of policy making, '\"scientists need to run for office.\"' He felt that 2018's California [[jungle primaries]] afforded him a better chance at making the final two for the general election, but he did not make the final two (which were Dianne Feinstein and [[Kevin de Le\u00f3n]]).<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\">{{cite web|last1=Krieger|first1=Lisa|title=Bay Area molecular biologist Michael Eisen announces bid for U.S. Senate|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/02/03/bay-area-molecular-biologist-michael-eisen-announces-bid-for-u-s-senate/|website=California News|publisher=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=7 February 2017|date=2017-02-04}}</ref>\n\n{{Cquote|For a really long time, scientists have watched political processes erode \u2014 and have watched politicians openly deride science, dismissing the role that science plays in our everyday life. Scientists have been sitting here hoping that someone would come along and defend those principals. Politics, in my mind, should function similar to science. We should try to figure out what\u2019s going on in the world and then debate the best way to do it, to make the world better. The best tools we have to characterize reality are the observational tools that science uses all the time. Too much of politics has rejected that basic principle that scientists live and breathe all the time.<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\"/>}}\nEisen dropped out of the race when he failed to qualify for the June 2018 primary ballot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Michael_Eisen|title=Michael Eisen|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Open Access advocacy==\nThroughout his career he has been an advocate for \"[[open science]]\", which is the free release of the material and intellectual product of scientific research. He is a leading advocate of [[Open access (publishing)|open access scientific publishing]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Eisen|first=Michael|title=Publish and be praised|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2003/oct/09/research.highereducation|accessdate=23 September 2013|newspaper=Guardian|date=8 October 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Brown | first1 = P. O. | authorlink1 = Patrick O. Brown| last2 = Eisen | first2 = M. B. | authorlink2 = Michael Eisen| last3 = Varmus | first3 = H. E. | authorlink3 = Harold E. Varmus| title = Why PLoS Became a Publisher | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.0000036 | journal = PLOS Biology | volume =  1| issue = 1 | pages =  E36| year = 2003 | pmid =  14551926| pmc = 212706}}</ref><ref>https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.04/rave_pr.html 2004 [[Wired Magazine]] Rave Awards \"For cracking the spine of the science cartel\"</ref> and is co-founder of [[PLOS|Public Library of Science (PLOS)]] and serves on the PLOS board, the Academic Steering & Advocacy Committee of [[Open Library of Humanities]],<ref>{{cite journal|last=Howard|first=Jennifer|title=Project Aims to Bring PLoS-Style Openness to the Humanities|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Project-Aims-to-Bring/136889/|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=19 November 2013|date=29 January 2013}}</ref> and is an adviser to [[Science Commons]].\n\nIn 2012 Eisen began protesting against the [[Research Works Act]] as part of his appeal to promote open access to information.<ref>{{cite magazine |url= https://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2012/01/congress-considers-paywalling-science-you-already-paid-for/ |title=Congress Considers Paywalling Science You Already Paid For |first=David |last=Dobbs |magazine=wired.com |date=6 January 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 2002, Eisen was awarded the inaugural [[Benjamin Franklin Award (Bioinformatics)|Benjamin Franklin Award]] in bioinformatics, for his work on [[PLOS]] and the open-access availability of his microarray cluster analysis software.<ref name=\"franklin-award\">{{cite web|title=Benjamin Franklin Award - Bioinformatics.org|url=http://www.bioinformatics.org/franklin/|website=www.bioinformatics.org|accessdate=7 February 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*[http://www.michaeleisen.org/blog/ It is NOT junk - Personal blog of Michael Eisen]\n*[http://www.michaeleisen.org/blog/?p=1967 Open letter to President Trump to replace [[Francis Collins]] as NIH Director]\n*[http://www.eisen2018.com/ Michael Eisen (I) for Senate]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{PLoS}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eisen, Michael}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American biologists]]\n[[Category:American bioinformaticians]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley faculty]]\n[[Category:Howard Hughes Medical Investigators]]\n[[Category:Founders]]\n[[Category:Public Library of Science people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Michael Eisen\n| birth_name = Michael Bruce Eisen\n|image             = Plos eisen.jpg \n|caption           = Michael Eisen\n| birth_date  ={{Birth date and age|1967|04|13}}\n|birth_place       = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]\n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = American\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Biology]] \n* [[Genetics]] \n* [[Genomics]] \n* [[Evolution]] \n* [[Developmental biology|Development]]<ref name=\"googlescholar\">{{GoogleScholar|z2foFg4AAAAJ}}</ref>}}\n|work_institutions = [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n|alma_mater        = [[Harvard College]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Don Craig Wiley]]{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n| thesis_title = Structural Studies of Influenza A Virus Proteins\n| thesis_url = https://books.google.com/books?id=e2wAHwAACAAJ\n| thesis_year = 1996\n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = [[PLOS|Public Library of Science (PLOS)]]\n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = [[Benjamin Franklin Award (Bioinformatics)]] (2002)\n|religion          = \n|footnotes         = \n|signature         =\n| website = {{Plainlist|\n* {{URL|eisenlab.org}}\n* {{URL|michaeleisen.org}}\n*{{URL|https://twitter.com/SenatorPhD}}}}\n\n}}'''Michael Bruce Eisen''' (born April 13, 1967) is an American computational biologist and the editor-in-chief of the journal [[eLife]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elifesciences.org/inside-elife/7eb55710/elife-welcomes-michael-eisen-as-editor-in-chief|title=eLife welcomes Michael Eisen as Editor-in-Chief|date=2019-03-05|website=eLife|language=en|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>. He is a professor of [[genetics]], [[genomics]] and [[Developmental biology|development]] at [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael B. Eisen, PhD|url=http://www.hhmi.org/scientists/michael-b-eisen|work=Howard Hughes Medical Institute|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"scopus\">{{Scopus|id=7004331829}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 10963602\n| year = 2000\n| last1 = Perou\n| first1 = C. M.\n| title = Molecular portraits of human breast tumours\n| journal = Nature\n| volume = 406\n| issue = 6797\n| pages = 747\u201352\n| last2 = S\u00f8rlie\n| first2 = T\n| last3 = Eisen\n| first3 = M. B.\n| last4 = Van De Rijn\n| first4 = M\n| last5 = Jeffrey\n| first5 = S. S.\n| last6 = Rees\n| first6 = C. A.\n| last7 = Pollack\n| first7 = J. R.\n| last8 = Ross\n| first8 = D. T.\n| last9 = Johnsen\n| first9 = H\n| last10 = Akslen\n| first10 = L. A.\n| last11 = Fluge\n| first11 = O\n| last12 = Pergamenschikov\n| first12 = A\n| last13 = Williams\n| first13 = C\n| last14 = Zhu\n| first14 = S. X.\n| last15 = L\u00f8nning\n| first15 = P. E.\n| last16 = B\u00f8rresen-Dale\n| first16 = A. L.\n| last17 = Brown\n| first17 = P. O.\n| last18 = Botstein\n| first18 = D\n| doi = 10.1038/35021093\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.283.5398.83| title = The Transcriptional Program in the Response of Human Fibroblasts to Serum| journal = Science| volume = 283| issue = 5398| pages = 83\u20137| year = 1999| last1 = Iyer | first1 = V. R. | pmid=9872747}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 10700174\n| year = 2000\n| last1 = Ross\n| first1 = D. T.\n| title = Systematic variation in gene expression patterns in human cancer cell lines\n| journal = Nature Genetics\n| volume = 24\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 227\u201335\n| last2 = Scherf\n| first2 = U\n| last3 = Eisen\n| first3 = M. B.\n| last4 = Perou\n| first4 = C. M.\n| last5 = Rees\n| first5 = C\n| last6 = Spellman\n| first6 = P\n| last7 = Iyer\n| first7 = V\n| last8 = Jeffrey\n| first8 = S. S.\n| last9 = Van De Rijn\n| first9 = M\n| last10 = Waltham\n| first10 = M\n| last11 = Pergamenschikov\n| first11 = A\n| last12 = Lee\n| first12 = J. C.\n| last13 = Lashkari\n| first13 = D\n| last14 = Shalon\n| first14 = D\n| last15 = Myers\n| first15 = T. G.\n| last16 = Weinstein\n| first16 = J. N.\n| last17 = Botstein\n| first17 = D\n| last18 = Brown\n| first18 = P. O.\n| doi = 10.1038/73432\n| url = https://cdr.lib.unc.edu/concern/articles/9p290c45r\n}}</ref> He is a leading advocate of [[Open access (publishing)|open access scientific publishing]] and is co-founder of [[PLOS|Public Library of Science (PLOS)]]. In 2018, Eisen announced his candidacy [[United States Senate election in California, 2018|U.S. Senate from California]] as an [[Independent politician|Independent]], though he failed to qualify for the ballot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/01/qa-michael-eisen-bids-be-first-fly-biologist-us-senate|title=Q&A: Michael Eisen bids to be first fly biologist in the U.S. Senate|last=CohenJan. 27|first=Jon|last2=2017|date=2017-01-27|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13|last3=Pm|first3=3:30}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in Boston, Eisen and his brother [[Jonathan Eisen|Jonathan]] were raised in a family of scientists. Their grandfather was an [[X-ray crystallography|x-ray crystallographer]], their father, Howard Eisen a physician, and mother, Laura<ref name=\"Laura Eisen Washington Post\">{{cite web|last1=Okie|first1=Susan|title=NIH SCIENTIST A SUICIDE AMID PROBE OF PAPER|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1987/02/14/nih-scientist-a-suicide-amid-probe-of-paper/e0cd2abe-4763-40f4-b839-8e86df4b2cbd/|work=Washington Post|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref> a biochemist. They moved to [[Bethesda, Maryland]] when Eisen was four or five years old. The brothers spent summers in Long Island with their grandparents. Eisen states that he loved frogs and salamanders '\"Even more than I have a frog fetish, I have a swamp fetish. I really like being in swamps.\"'  He was also very interested in math and was captain of the high school math team. Eisen graduated from [[Walt Whitman High School (Bethesda, Maryland)|Walt Whitman High School]] in 1985. Intending to major in mathematics at Harvard University, he realized that there [he may encounter] other more brilliant math students, it was a ''[[Good Will Hunting]]'' moment and he decided that he did not want to major in mathematics, '\"You don't want to be Salieri to Mozart.\"' During his years at Harvard, Eisen worked on \"unlocking the three-dimensional structures of proteins.\" He was shown a [[DNA microarray]] which taught him a '\"new way of doing biology\"'.<ref name=\"Mechanic Mother Jones\">{{cite web|last1=Mechanic|first1=Michael|title=Steal This Research Paper! (You Already Paid for It.)|url=https://www.motherjones.com/media/2013/09/michael-eisen-plos-open-access-aaron-swartz|publisher=Mother Jones|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nEisen completed his PhD at [[Harvard University]] in biophysics and a B.S. (also from Harvard) in Math.<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\"/>  He was under the supervision of [[Don Craig Wiley]]<ref name=\"India Bio Science\"/> while studying [[Influenza A virus]] Proteins.<ref name=\"eisenphd\">{{cite thesis|degree=PhD|first=Michael Bruce |last=Eisen|title=Structural Studies of Influenza A Virus Proteins|publisher=Harvard University |date=1996|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e2wAHwAACAAJ| authorlink=Michael Eisen|oclc=48938206}}</ref>\n\n{{Cquote|There are things that are really really difficult, those are the kinds of problems you do want to work on. It's not that easy to tell the difference between impossible problems and a problem that is really really difficult. But learning to do so is critically important. - Things I learned from working with Pat Brown - 2015 <ref name=\"India Bio Science\"/>}}\n\nAfter earning his doctorate, Eisen was a Postdoctoral Fellow at [[Stanford University]] in the lab of [[David Botstein]], where he most notably developed a method for interpreting gene expression data from microarrays. The seminal research publication that Eisen authored about this project has been cited over 16,000 times.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Eisen|first1=MB|last2=Spellman|first2=PT|last3=Brown|first3=PO|last4=Botstein|first4=D|title=Cluster analysis and display of genome-wide expression patterns|journal=Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A|date=8 December 1998|volume=95|issue=25|pages=14863\u20138|pmid=9843981|doi=10.1073/pnas.95.25.14863|pmc=24541}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nHis academic research focuses on the [[evolution]] of [[gene regulation]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Eisen | first1 = M. \n| authorlink1 = Michael Eisen\n| last2 = Spellman | first2 = P. \n| last3 = Brown | first3 = P. \n| authorlink3 = Patrick O. Brown\n| last4 = Botstein | first4 = D. \n| authorlink4 = David Botstein\n| title = Cluster analysis and display of genome-wide expression patterns \n| journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America \n| volume = 95 \n| issue = 25 \n| pages = 14863\u201314868 \n| year = 1998 \n| pmid = 9843981 \n| pmc = 24541 | doi=10.1073/pnas.95.25.14863\n}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Alizadeh | first1 = A. A. | last2 = Eisen | first2 = M. B. | authorlink2 = Michael Eisen | last3 = Davis | first3 = R. E. | last4 = Ma | first4 = C. | last5 = Lossos | first5 = I. S. | last6 = Rosenwald | first6 = A. | last7 = Boldrick | first7 = J. C. | last8 = Sabet | first8 = H. | last9 = Tran | first9 = T. | last10 = Yu | first10 = X. | last11 = Powell | first11 = J. I. | last12 = Yang | first12 = L. | last13 = Marti | first13 = G. E. | last14 = Moore | first14 = T. | last15 = Hudson Jr | first15 = J. | last16 = Lu | first16 = L. | last17 = Lewis | first17 = D. B. | last18 = Tibshirani | first18 = R. | last19 = Sherlock | first19 = G. | last20 = Chan | first20 = W. C. | last21 = Greiner | first21 = T. C. | last22 = Weisenburger | first22 = D. D. | last23 = Armitage | first23 = J. O. | last24 = Warnke | first24 = R. | last25 = Levy | first25 = R. | last26 = Wilson | first26 = W. | last27 = Grever | first27 = M. R. | last28 = Byrd | first28 = J. C. | last29 = Botstein | first29 = D. | last30 = Brown | first30 = P. O. | title = Distinct types of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma identified by gene expression profiling | journal = Nature | volume = 403 | issue = 6769 | pages = 503\u2013511 | year = 2000 | pmid = 10676951 | doi = 10.1038/35000501}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 17994087\n| year = 2007\n| last1 = Drosophila 12 Genomes\n| first1 = Consortium\n| title = Evolution of genes and genomes on the Drosophila phylogeny\n| journal = Nature\n| volume = 450\n| issue = 7167\n| pages = 203\u201318\n| last2 = Clark\n| first2 = A. G.\n| last3 = Eisen\n| first3 = M. B.\n| authorlink3 = Michael Eisen\n| last4 = Smith\n| first4 = D. R.\n| last5 = Bergman\n| first5 = C. M.\n| last6 = Oliver\n| first6 = B\n| last7 = Markow\n| first7 = T. A.\n| last8 = Kaufman\n| first8 = T. C.\n| last9 = Kellis\n| first9 = M\n| last10 = Gelbart\n| first10 = W\n| last11 = Iyer\n| first11 = V. N.\n| last12 = Pollard\n| first12 = D. A.\n| last13 = Sackton\n| first13 = T. B.\n| last14 = Larracuente\n| first14 = A. M.\n| last15 = Singh\n| first15 = N. D.\n| last16 = Abad\n| first16 = J. P.\n| last17 = Abt\n| first17 = D. N.\n| last18 = Adryan\n| first18 = B\n| last19 = Aguade\n| first19 = M\n| last20 = Akashi\n| first20 = H\n| last21 = Anderson\n| first21 = W. W.\n| last22 = Aquadro\n| first22 = C. F.\n| last23 = Ardell\n| first23 = D. H.\n| last24 = Arguello\n| first24 = R\n| last25 = Artieri\n| first25 = C. G.\n| last26 = Barbash\n| first26 = D. A.\n| last27 = Barker\n| first27 = D\n| last28 = Barsanti\n| first28 = P\n| last29 = Batterham\n| first29 = P\n| last30 = Batzoglou\n| first30 = S\n| display-authors = 29\n| doi = 10.1038/nature06341\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1091/mbc.9.12.3273| title = Comprehensive Identification of Cell Cycle-regulated Genes of the Yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae by Microarray Hybridization| journal = Molecular Biology of the Cell| volume = 9| issue = 12| pages = 3273\u201397| year = 1998| last1 = Spellman | first1 = P. T.| last2 = Sherlock | first2 = G.| last3 = Zhang | first3 = M. Q.| last4 = Iyer | first4 = V. R.| last5 = Anders | first5 = K.| last6 = Eisen | first6 = M. B.| last7 = Brown | first7 = P. O.| last8 = Botstein | first8 = D.| last9 = Futcher | first9 = B. | pmid=9843569 | pmc=25624}}</ref> Despite this focus, Eisen\u2019s work has historically spanned very diverse disciplines. For example, his 5 most cited papers  cover a broad range of topics including methods for [[hierarchical clustering]]<ref name=\":1\" />, applications to human [[Breast cancer|breast cancers]] (with [[David Botstein]] and Charles Perou)<ref name=\":0\" />, and discovery of tumor subtypes in [[Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma|diffuse large B cell lymphoma]] (with [[Ash Alizadeh]] and [[Louis Staudt]])<ref name=\":2\" />. His more research work has been on [[Drosophilidae|fruit flies]] and [[Drosophila]]<ref name=\"HarmonNYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/06/science/donald-trump-scientists-politics.html?smprod=nytcore-ipad&smid=nytcore-ipad-share&_r=1|title=In Age of Trump, Scientists Show Signs of a Political Pulse|last1=Harmon|first1=Amy|author2=Henry Fountain|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=NYT|accessdate=7 February 2017|date=2017-02-06}}</ref> and how they \"develop from a tiny single-celled egg to a mature adult. He says they hold insights into what goes wrong in people as they age.\"<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\"/> He receives funding from the [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]] for his research.<ref name=\"HarmonNYT\"/>\n\n==2018 U.S. Senate race==\nEisen announced through Twitter on January 25 his intent to run for [[2018 United States Senate election in California|U.S. Senate from California in 2018]] for Democratic Senator [[Dianne Feinstein]]'s seat, registering the Twitter handle ''SenatorPhD''.<ref name=\"Reardon Nature\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/news/geneticist-launches-bid-for-us-senate-1.21381|title=Geneticist launches bid for US Senate|last1=Reardon|first1=Sara|journal=Nature|accessdate=7 February 2017|doi=10.1038/nature.2017.21381|year=2017}}</ref> His campaign slogan was \"Liberty, Equality, Reality\". Eisen's reasons for running for Congress included his belief that the [[Donald Trump|Trump administration]] is unresponsive to [[climate change]] and other science-related issues. Another reason Eisen decided to run was his experience watching Cabinet appointees being interviewed by the Senate about climate change. He thought '\u201cIt would be really nice to have scientists ask the questions of the Cabinet appointees, because the senators don\u2019t seem to understand the issue and aren\u2019t asking the right questions.\u201d'<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\" /> He feels that if science is to be on the forefront of policy making, '\"scientists need to run for office.\"' He felt that 2018's California [[jungle primaries]] afforded him a better chance at making the final two for the general election, but he did not make the final two (which were Dianne Feinstein and [[Kevin de Le\u00f3n]]).<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\">{{cite web|last1=Krieger|first1=Lisa|title=Bay Area molecular biologist Michael Eisen announces bid for U.S. Senate|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/02/03/bay-area-molecular-biologist-michael-eisen-announces-bid-for-u-s-senate/|website=California News|publisher=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=7 February 2017|date=2017-02-04}}</ref>\n\n{{Cquote|For a really long time, scientists have watched political processes erode \u2014 and have watched politicians openly deride science, dismissing the role that science plays in our everyday life. Scientists have been sitting here hoping that someone would come along and defend those principals. Politics, in my mind, should function similar to science. We should try to figure out what\u2019s going on in the world and then debate the best way to do it, to make the world better. The best tools we have to characterize reality are the observational tools that science uses all the time. Too much of politics has rejected that basic principle that scientists live and breathe all the time.<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\"/>}}\nEisen dropped out of the race when he failed to qualify for the June 2018 primary ballot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Michael_Eisen|title=Michael Eisen|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Open Access advocacy===\nThroughout his career he has been an advocate for \"[[open science]]\", which is the free release of the material and intellectual product of scientific research. He is a leading advocate of [[Open access (publishing)|open access scientific publishing]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Eisen|first=Michael|title=Publish and be praised|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2003/oct/09/research.highereducation|accessdate=23 September 2013|newspaper=Guardian|date=8 October 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Brown | first1 = P. O. | authorlink1 = Patrick O. Brown| last2 = Eisen | first2 = M. B. | authorlink2 = Michael Eisen| last3 = Varmus | first3 = H. E. | authorlink3 = Harold E. Varmus| title = Why PLoS Became a Publisher | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.0000036 | journal = PLOS Biology | volume =  1| issue = 1 | pages =  E36| year = 2003 | pmid =  14551926| pmc = 212706}}</ref><ref>https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.04/rave_pr.html 2004 [[Wired Magazine]] Rave Awards \"For cracking the spine of the science cartel\"</ref> and is co-founder of [[PLOS|Public Library of Science (PLOS)]] and serves on the PLOS board, the Academic Steering & Advocacy Committee of [[Open Library of Humanities]],<ref>{{cite journal|last=Howard|first=Jennifer|title=Project Aims to Bring PLoS-Style Openness to the Humanities|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Project-Aims-to-Bring/136889/|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=19 November 2013|date=29 January 2013}}</ref> and is an adviser to [[Science Commons]].\n\nIn 2012 Eisen began protesting against the [[Research Works Act]] as part of his appeal to promote open access to information.<ref>{{cite magazine |url= https://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2012/01/congress-considers-paywalling-science-you-already-paid-for/ |title=Congress Considers Paywalling Science You Already Paid For |first=David |last=Dobbs |magazine=wired.com |date=6 January 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Baseball and biology ===\n\nWhen Eisen lived in Tennessee he worked as a [[Sports commentator|play-by-play announcer]] for a minor league baseball team,<ref name=\"Merc Krieger\"/> the [[Columbia Mules]]. He is <!-- 8===8 --> a self-proclaimed [[Red Sox]] fanatic.<ref name=\"Mechanic Mother Jones\"/> He and computational biologist, James Fraser recorded a video for iBiology about the role baseball statistics influenced their research. Their argument is that sequencing DNA is similar to scoring a baseball game, and that many computational biologists learned to think about science computations from an obsessive interest in baseball stats. The exercise of comparing a specific player's stats to a database of other similar players allows a baseball fan to predict future performance. This same system works with proteins and predicting functions. As tools are developed that break down and track all stats concerning baseball players, so will technology improve with genetics. With both baseball and genetics, tools are being developed that refine the models.<ref name=\"Fraser Eisen Baseball\">{{cite web|title=James Fraser & Michael Eisen: Baseball Meets Biology|url=https://www.ibiology.org/ibiomagazine/issue-6/james-fraser-michael-eisen-baseball-meets-biology.html|website=Education|publisher=iBiology|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>  In a lecture in 2015, Eisen stated that he received a computer from his grandfather for his twelfth birthday and spent the next five years teaching himself how to program so that he could keep track of baseball stats.<ref name=\"India Bio Science\">{{cite web|title=Michael Eisen: Baseball, mathematics and biology|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BACy6Lsi6-U|publisher=India Bio Science|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 2002, Eisen was awarded the inaugural [[Benjamin Franklin Award (Bioinformatics)|Benjamin Franklin Award]] in bioinformatics, for his work on [[PLOS]] and the open-access availability of his microarray cluster analysis software.<ref name=\"franklin-award\">{{cite web|title=Benjamin Franklin Award - Bioinformatics.org|url=http://www.bioinformatics.org/franklin/|website=www.bioinformatics.org|accessdate=7 February 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*[http://www.michaeleisen.org/blog/ It is NOT junk - Personal blog of Michael Eisen]\n*[http://www.michaeleisen.org/blog/?p=1967 Open letter to President Trump to replace [[Francis Collins]] as NIH Director]\n*[http://www.eisen2018.com/ Michael Eisen (I) for Senate]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{PLoS}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eisen, Michael}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American biologists]]\n[[Category:American bioinformaticians]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley faculty]]\n[[Category:Howard Hughes Medical Investigators]]\n[[Category:Founders]]\n[[Category:Public Library of Science people]]\n", "name_user": "Amkilpatrick", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reordering. Not sure this is the best place for the 'biology and baseball' section either though", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Eisen"}
